Got it — that usually means GitHub is expecting a different branch or there’s already a commit in the remote repo that you haven’t pulled. Here's how to resolve it depending on your scenario:

🔧 Most Likely Fix: Force Push (Safe on New Repo)

Since your GitHub repo is likely empty or only has an auto-generated README, you can force push your local version.

⚠️ Only do this if you're sure you're not overwriting anything important.

bash
git push -u origin main --force

✅ Explanation

This command will:

  • Upload your local main branch

  • Replace anything already in the GitHub repo (like a placeholder README)

🛡 Optional: If You Want to Merge Instead (Safer)

If you want to pull first (like if you added a README on GitHub):

bash
git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories
git push -u origin main

This avoids force pushing, but you’ll be asked to resolve a merge commit message in your terminal editor.

Got it — sounds like we need to refine the mobile behavior of the horizontal scroll layout so that each section stacks vertically on small screens, rather than locking to just the first panel.

Let’s fix that now.

🔍 What’s Likely Happening:

Your index.html uses a structure like:

html
<div class="horizontal-scroll">
  <section class="panel"> ... </section>
  <section class="panel"> ... </section>
  ...
</div>

And the .horizontal-scroll container likely has something like this in the CSS:

css
.horizontal-scroll {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  overflow-x: auto;
  scroll-snap-type: x mandatory;
}

This works beautifully on desktop — but on mobile, you want vertical stacking, not horizontal scroll.

✅ Fix: Use @media queries to switch to vertical on mobile

We’ll inject this CSS:

html
<style>
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .horizontal-scroll {
      display: block !important;
      overflow-x: unset !important;
      scroll-snap-type: none !important;
    }
    .panel {
      width: 100vw !important;
      height: auto !important;
      scroll-snap-align: none !important;
    }
  }
</style>
